steps.content:
To make it easier to solve for time $t$, let's rewrite the equation in exponential form. Exponentiating both sides:

$$
\begin{aligned}
e^{\ln(T - 20)} &= e^{-0.1t + \ln(60)} \\
T - 20 &= e^{-0.1t} \cdot e^{\ln(60)} \\
T - 20 &= 60e^{-0.1t}
\end{aligned}
$$

Adding 20 to both sides gives us the general model for the temperature at any time $t$:
$$T = 20 + 60e^{-0.1t}$$

We need to find the time $t$ when the temperature is $50^\circ \mathrm{C}$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
50 &= 20 + 60e^{-0.1t} \\
30 &= 60e^{-0.1t} \\
0.5 &= e^{-0.1t}
\end{aligned}
$$

Taking the natural log of both sides:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\ln(0.5) &= -0.1t \\
t &= \frac{\ln(0.5)}{-0.1} \approx 6.931 \text{ minutes}
\end{aligned}
$$
